    "analysis": "From the previous aggregated scan we see consistent anomalies across all five candidate services: memory ('mem') for each service has every point in-window (25 points) and exceeds its global P95; disk I/O ('diskio') is also elevated with early anomalies (e.g., ts-auth-service diskio max 190,866 vs P95 84,255). Trace and log row_count metrics are high for ts-train, ts-route, and ts-travel. These metric signals narrow the likely resource faults to memory and disk I/O across services, with disk I/O on ts-auth-service showing a large breach. To move from anomaly detection to fault identification, we must locate consecutive fault segments (consecutive minutes where metric > global_p95) per component-KPI, measure their durations and severity, and rank them. The next step is to extract fault segments for metric KPIs (at least 'mem' and 'diskio') for the five candidate services within the incident window and report start/end, length, max value, P95, and severity so we can decide which faulty component is most likely the root cause.",
