    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, restrict rows to cmdb_id in [ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service] and focus on kpi_name values 'mem' and 'diskio'. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name): 1) compute global_p95 over the full available series (do NOT filter by incident window for this step). 2) Filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-23 18:47:25 -> 2024-01-23 19:17:25 UTC and find consecutive fault segments where value > global_p95. Treat consecutive timestamps as 60 seconds apart. For each fault segment return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, start_ts_utc, end_ts_utc, length_minutes, max_value, global_p95, severity_ratio = (max_value - global_p95) / global_p95. Also return the number of distinct services that have at least one fault segment. Limit output to top 20 segments sorted by severity_ratio descending." }

{
    "analysis": "From the metric fault-segmentation step we identified faults on multiple services but one stands out: a short, large disk I/O spike on ts-auth-service around 2024-01-23T18:50–18:51Z (severity ≈ +126% above its global P95). Other services show smaller diskio spikes and very small mem breaches (fractions of a percent). According to the workflow, we now need trace analysis to decide whether ts-auth-service is the root-cause service (i.e., whether it is the downstream faulty service in affected call chains) or whether other service(s) downstream of it are the root cause. Specifically, we should inspect trace metrics that indicate calls from/to ts-auth-service (trace.from_ts-auth-service.*, trace.to_ts-auth-service.*) and service self/duration metrics for candidate services to see call directions and whether ts-auth-service shows anomalous trace counts or latency within the incident window. This will help confirm whether the ts-auth-service disk I/O spike is the causal root cause or whether it is a secondary effect.",
